Done. `sayHello()` is now stateful — it persists a counter in the DO's embedded SQLite database and increments it atomically on every call.

```9:30:apps/durable-objects/src/index.ts
export class MyDurableObject extends DurableObject<Env> {
  constructor(ctx: DurableObjectState, env: Env) {
    super(ctx, env);
    // Runs once per instance load (cold start / after hibernation), before any
    // request is handled, so the table always exists when sayHello() runs.
    this.ctx.storage.sql.exec(
      "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS counter (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, value INTEGER NOT NULL)",
    );
  }

  async sayHello(): Promise<string> {
    const row = this.ctx.storage.sql
      .exec<{ value: number }>(
        `INSERT INTO counter (id, value) VALUES (1, 1)
         ON CONFLICT(id) DO UPDATE SET value = value + 1
         RETURNING value`,
      )
      .one();
    return `Hello, World! (call #${row.value})`;
  }
}
```

How it behaves:
- Each call returns `Hello, World! (call #1)`, `#2`, `#3`, … and the count **survives hibernation/restarts** because it lives in durable SQLite storage, not in-memory.
- The count is **per DO instance** (per name). Since the Worker uses `getByName(url.pathname)`, each distinct path is its own object with its own independent counter — e.g. `/foo` and `/bar` count separately.
- The `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... RETURNING` does the read-increment-write in a single atomic SQL statement, so concurrent requests to the same instance won't race.

Type-check passes (exit 0). Try it:

```bash
cd apps/durable-objects
bun run dev
# then in another terminal:
curl http://localhost:8787/        # Hello, World! (call #1)
curl http://localhost:8787/        # Hello, World! (call #2)
curl http://localhost:8787/other   # Hello, World! (call #1)  — separate instance
```

