The key insight is that runners accept inert `Coroutine` specs, not already-started handles, which keeps ownership clean: the runner creates a scope, starts each coroutine as a child under it, and on failure cancels siblings (fail-fast behavior). Also moving `cancelGracefully()` and `cancelled` from `Coroutine` to `RoutineHandle` makes sense — the inert coroutine only needs `.await()` and `.start()`, and you can't call cancel without a handle anyway since you only get one after starting.

For futures and other blocking operations, `fut.await()` returning a `RoutineHandle` is actually elegant: it makes the wait itself cancellable (you can stop waiting without cancelling the future). This unifies the model — any blocking operation returns a handle so the wait is cancellable. Channel operations are different though; they don't need their own handles since they're cancelled via the ambient scope when the enclosing coroutine is cancelled.

The cleanest approach is to distinguish between user-defined coroutines and library primitives: `io.coroutine(fn)` stays inert and lazy (only thenable after `.start()` or `.await()`), while primitives like `chan.receive()`, futures, and `mutex.acquire()` are directly awaitable since they're inherently "started" operations with no laziness concern. Cancellation for primitives flows through the ambient scope, so they don't need their own cancel handles. This keeps the API ergonomic and only adds the Coroutine/handle ceremony where it actually matters. Runners like `io.all`, `io.race`, and `io.background` will accept inert `Coroutine`s, manage their startup themselves, and return `RoutineHandle`s so the whole group is cancellable — I'm leaning toward `io.all` failing fast and canceling siblings when one fails. I think I've got enough clarity now to move forward: I'll endorse their `RoutineHandle` design, lay out a concrete revised type sketch with the normalized rules, flag the couple of remaining semantic choices (`io.all` failure behavior and `cancelGracefully` timeout), and propose we lock this in and write it into a proper DESIGN.md rather than keep iterating.

