Great question — and A handles it cleanly; the key is distinguishing **values** from the **close signal**:

- **Values are competing-consumer (work-queue) delivery.** Each value goes to exactly **one** receiver. With N consumers all doing `for await (const v of chan)` on the same channel, the runtime hands each sent value to one waiting consumer, FIFO among waiters (longest-waiting receiver served first). This is exactly your draft's producer + 3-consumer + waitgroup pattern — load-balanced work, not duplicated.
- **Close is a broadcast.** `close()` wakes **all** waiting receivers at once. Any buffered values are distributed one-each to waiters in FIFO order; once drained, **every** consumer observes end-of-stream simultaneously — so all N `for await...of` loops terminate cleanly, and any explicit `receive()` calls throw `ChannelClosedError`. No consumer is left hanging.

So multi-consumer "just works":

```ts
const chan = io.channel<number>({ capacity: 10 });
const consume = () => io.coroutine(async () => {
  for await (const v of chan) handle(v);   // each v to exactly one consumer; loop ends on close
});
io.background([consume(), consume(), consume()]);
// producer sends..., then chan.close() -> all three loops drain + exit
```

The one thing this does **not** do is **broadcast/fan-out** (every consumer sees every value) — that's a different primitive (pub/sub topic), because a channel is a hand-off queue, not a broadcast bus. Your draft only needs competing-consumer, so channel-as-work-queue covers it. The question is whether you also want a broadcast primitive in scope now.

The user is asking how multiple consumers work with a closed channel—specifically, whether `for await...of chan` and `receive()` throwing on a closed+drained channel creates issues. I'm realizing that with standard channel semantics, each value goes to exactly one consumer (work-stealing pattern), not broadcast to all of them, similar to how Go channels behave.

When the channel closes, though, that's a broadcast signal: all waiting receivers unblock, buffered values get distributed one-per-consumer in FIFO order, and once drained, every remaining and future receiver sees end-of-stream. So `for await...of` loops all terminate cleanly, and `receive()` calls all throw. This matches Go's behavior perfectly—values are competing-consumer load-balanced, but the close signal wakes everyone simultaneously.

I should clarify the distinction though: this channel design is a work queue with competing consumers, not a pub/sub broadcast where each consumer gets every value. If they need that kind of fan-out, that's a separate primitive. But for their use case with the producer and three consumers, option A handles it exactly right.

